T* (Key Findings) Tj
T* (- Low headline rates in China's banking system do not necessarily reach borrowers that fail) Tj
T* (rigid regulatory or social-credit screening requirements.) Tj
T* (- A meaningful group of profitable private companies can be unable to borrow from banks at) Tj
T* (any price despite robust cash flow and collateral.) Tj
T* (- The retreat of foreign distressed investors and the collapse of much domestic shadow) Tj
T* (banking have left China's private credit market chronically underserved.) Tj
T* () Tj
T* (China's interest rates are scraping historic lows, and yet private credit opportunities in) Tj
T* (the country are among the best in the world. Such a paradoxical situation is the consequence) Tj
T* (of overinclusive credit-screening regulations and an underserved market.) Tj
T* () Tj
T* (The reason cheap credit at the top of China's banking system doesn't translate into cheap) Tj
T* (credit for every borrower is that access, not price, is the real constraint. Capital doesn't) Tj
T* (move freely or efficiently between pools of the financial system, so low rates in one) Tj
T* (segment don't necessarily reach another. A meaningful segment of otherwise creditworthy) Tj
T* (private companies in China simply cannot borrow from banks at any price, because they fail) Tj
T* (to check a box involving a regulatory or social credit requirement that has little to do) Tj
T* (with their actual creditworthiness. That gap between rate and access is where ShoreVest) Tj
T* (operates, and it creates a unique opportunity that few investors are positioned to seize.) Tj
T* () Tj
T* (Cheap Credit…For the Few) Tj
T* (China's own credit data shows just how wide that gap has become.) Tj
T* () Tj
T* (The People's Bank of China \(PBoC\) has barely touched its policy rate in recent years. The) Tj
T* (last cut was 10 bps in May 2025, but weak credit demand among the segment of borrowers with) Tj
T* (access is driving real rates down.) Tj
T* () Tj
T* (In May, total social financing \(Beijing's measure of total credit in the economy\) grew by) Tj
T* (only 7.7% y/y, the slowest pace since the measure was introduced almost a decade ago. Bank) Tj
T* (lending was even slower, growing only 5.5%. Meanwhile, a surge in household savings since) Tj
T* (the pandemic means banks are awash with deposits they don't need. Banks would ideally like) Tj
T* (to cut deposit rates, but they're limited by the regulatory regime. Instead, many are) Tj
T* (striving to deter depositors and reduce their funding costs by offering fewer longer-tenor) Tj
T* (\(three-years and up\) fixed-term deposits or not offering them at all.) Tj
T* () Tj
T* (Fixed-income yields have also been declining, prompting many firms to issue bonds and use) Tj
T* (the proceeds to repay bank loans. To compete with both the bond market and each other for) Tj
T* (the segment of borrowers with access \(i.e. who check all boxes\), banks have been making) Tj
T* (loans at progressively lower interest rates. At the end of March, 48.8% of all bank loans) Tj
T* (had been lent out at below the loan prime rate \(LPR\), up from 42.4% at the beginning of) Tj
T* (2024. The loan prime rate is supposed to be the rate banks offer their best clients, and yet) Tj
